1
00:00:00,031 --> 00:00:17,989
Foundation Course 1, Talk 6 The Second Noble Truth, Karma Vipaka Karma, more commonly known in its Sanskrit form as Karma, another language the Buddhist scriptures are written in, has become part of our language ever since the hippie sixties.

2
00:00:18,862 --> 00:00:22,588
But unfortunately the meaning of the word has been overloaded with Hindu and Western ideas.

3
00:00:23,190 --> 00:00:32,143
In Buddhism, the law of karma is understood within the framework of the Four Noble Truths, and without this law, the truth would not make sense.

4
00:00:34,828 --> 00:00:45,984
The Buddha taught there were fundamental laws that governed our lives, and if we were able to perceive them, we would be able to understand why we suffer and how we could rid ourselves of suffering.

5
00:00:47,094 --> 00:00:55,106
Nowadays the word karma tends to be used when something bad happens to us, but actually it refers to everything that happens to us, good, bad and indifferent.

6
00:00:55,887 --> 00:00:58,970
Strictly speaking, karma means what we actually do.

7
00:00:59,551 --> 00:01:02,996
The results of our actions is properly termed viparka.

8
00:01:03,737 --> 00:01:09,284
These two words then mean cause and effect, action and result, karma, viparka.

9
00:01:11,328 --> 00:01:14,772
The law of cause and effect is accepted without question in western science.

10
00:01:15,242 --> 00:01:17,406
Nothing happens without something having caused it.

11
00:01:18,346 --> 00:01:21,251
There is nothing that just appears out of nowhere, so to speak.

12
00:01:22,233 --> 00:01:24,174
Everything is caused by something else.

13
00:01:25,376 --> 00:01:30,804
At its most obvious, the seed is the cause of the plant and the plant of the fruit, which in turn produces the seed.

14
00:01:31,926 --> 00:01:38,635
Buddhism takes this law of causality, of causation, and places it firmly within the moral sphere of human existence.

15
00:01:40,453 --> 00:01:45,939
Here we need to stand back a minute and consider what human beings are in relationship to each other and the world.

16
00:01:47,042 --> 00:01:54,930
I am autonomous in the sense that I have my own apparatus, body, senses, mental abilities and so on, which perceive the world and make sense of it.

17
00:01:55,391 --> 00:01:57,194
In this sense, I'm an individual unit.

18
00:01:57,813 --> 00:02:04,923
However, this unit is in a state of total relationship with the world, not just other human beings, but animals, plants and minerals.

19
00:02:06,704 --> 00:02:08,646
I have a relationship with the stones in the street.

20
00:02:08,907 --> 00:02:09,448
I kick them.

21
00:02:10,153 --> 00:02:25,722
In other words, although I in myself have my own understandings, thoughts and so on, as soon as I speak or act, I form a relationship with something or somebody, and this relationship in turn affects the way I think and understand.

22
00:02:26,402 --> 00:02:29,108
In a way, I can say I am my relationships.

23
00:02:30,420 --> 00:02:35,145
For instance, when Jim goes to work, he always sits at the same table, in the same chair.

24
00:02:35,566 --> 00:02:46,475
He has a relationship with these two objects, little do they know, whereby they are singled out from all the other tables and chairs in the room, singled out by him as his, belonging to him.

25
00:02:47,276 --> 00:02:48,639
He knows this is true for him.

26
00:02:49,680 --> 00:02:53,483
The chair and table don't, but it does affect them because no one else uses them.

27
00:02:54,243 --> 00:02:57,407
Their use, their relationship, is limited to Jim.

28
00:02:58,213 --> 00:03:01,717
and everyone else who works in that room agrees with that relationship.

29
00:03:03,060 --> 00:03:07,705
It's all very reciprocal and harmonious, since everyone else in the room has their own table and chair.

30
00:03:09,268 --> 00:03:12,812
One day Jim walks in, and lo and behold, someone is sitting at his table.

31
00:03:13,532 --> 00:03:14,774
This person is new to the place.

32
00:03:15,254 --> 00:03:16,036
She doesn't realise.

33
00:03:16,917 --> 00:03:23,245
In fact, she's only there temporarily to do a quick jotting, but her posture suggests that she owns the table and chair.

34
00:03:23,745 --> 00:03:27,629
She's pulled the chair right up, and is sitting comfortably and squarely at the table.

35
00:03:28,723 --> 00:03:30,828
She's taken his space.

36
00:03:32,389 --> 00:03:33,372
What is Jim's reaction?

37
00:03:34,213 --> 00:03:34,514
Anger.

38
00:03:35,134 --> 00:03:36,638
He might clothe it with sarcasm.

39
00:03:37,239 --> 00:03:38,039
Being promoted then?

40
00:03:38,801 --> 00:03:41,747
Sorry, she says, collects her thing and shoots off with an angry glance.

41
00:03:42,587 --> 00:03:53,247
You can see that in this little scene, Jim's relationship to that chair and table has been an underlying factor in making an enemy of someone who in all innocence was just using them temporarily.

42
00:03:54,239 --> 00:04:00,328
These attitudes we have within ourselves, our inner dispositions, affect our relationship to the world, both good and bad.

43
00:04:02,229 --> 00:04:05,855
Here is the Buddha firmly placing the centre of all our relationships.

44
00:04:07,277 --> 00:04:17,192
In this fathom-long body, I declare, is the world, the origin of the world, the cessation of the world, and the path leading to the cessation of the world.

45
00:04:19,079 --> 00:04:23,005
This is another formulation of the Four Noble Truths, but from the point of view of karma.

46
00:04:23,706 --> 00:04:35,266
As far as I am concerned, this me in myself, my existence, my sufferings, my joys, my birth, my death, is the world, the world as I know and perceive it, the world as I experience it.

47
00:04:35,786 --> 00:04:37,069
That world is me.

48
00:04:37,129 --> 00:04:44,682
I make divisions between me and myself and me with others, and also between me and the world.

49
00:04:45,454 --> 00:05:14,483
but actually this me in the world is just the me in myself portrayed upon the world affecting it and the me within myself is the world portrayed in me affecting me the division of subject and object is very much needed in ordinary daily life but we think of them as two totally separated things instead of realizing their intimate interrelationship the table chair and woman in the office have their own existence in the world

50
00:05:14,716 --> 00:05:16,177
their relationship to the world.

51
00:05:16,617 --> 00:05:22,603
But when Jim enters the scene, their existence in the world, their relationship to the world, includes him in it.

52
00:05:23,884 --> 00:05:27,648
When he entered the office, he fell into an immediate relationship with these three.

53
00:05:28,709 --> 00:05:31,951
What matters to Jim is exactly this interrelationship.

54
00:05:32,892 --> 00:05:37,958
The way he understands, perceives others, also includes the way others perceive and understand him.

55
00:05:37,997 --> 00:05:43,642
The way Jim understands and perceives things is very much affected by the way things affect him.

56
00:05:44,702 --> 00:05:48,228
When Jim doesn't see this, he lives in a dual world of me and them.

57
00:05:48,269 --> 00:05:51,894
Me, the isolated being in a world of things and others.

58
00:05:53,076 --> 00:05:56,641
But in actual fact, everything is interdependent, interrelated.

59
00:05:57,322 --> 00:05:59,144
It's like a huge folk dance.

60
00:05:59,165 --> 00:06:03,651
Each one of us are only individuals in that we have a specific role to play within the whole dance.

61
00:06:04,494 --> 00:06:09,141
How we play that role is up to us, though our decisions will be affected by the other dancers.

62
00:06:11,230 --> 00:06:16,555
We say it takes two to start a quarrel, but you can bet your last penny the protagonists will blame each other.

63
00:06:17,196 --> 00:06:19,177
They won't see it as an inter-relationship.

64
00:06:21,221 --> 00:06:24,803
If the woman was sitting at another desk, Jim might have barely noticed her.

65
00:06:25,305 --> 00:06:27,387
If the woman had been a friend, he would have greeted her.

66
00:06:28,067 --> 00:06:35,735
So you can see, within this fathom-long body is the whole world, with all its suffering, and of course the path leading out of suffering too.

67
00:06:36,644 --> 00:06:42,110
This whole world is the whole of the interdependent interrelationships we are.

68
00:06:44,774 --> 00:06:52,884
Now, within this world of interdependent interrelationships, when we think or do something which is karma, we create a result, viparka.

69
00:06:53,845 --> 00:06:58,951
In our minds, we either create a different way of thinking or we reinforce an old way of thinking.

70
00:06:59,572 --> 00:07:01,875
In other words, we are conditioning ourselves.

71
00:07:03,172 --> 00:07:06,055
Every day, when Jim gets to work, he has a cup of coffee.

72
00:07:06,776 --> 00:07:10,000
As soon as he walks into the office, his first thought is coffee.

73
00:07:11,081 --> 00:07:11,382
Why?

74
00:07:11,822 --> 00:07:14,406
Because for the past few years, that's what he's always done.

75
00:07:15,468 --> 00:07:18,771
He sometimes looks forward to the coffee, even on the way to work.

76
00:07:19,151 --> 00:07:22,336
His thoughts keep reminding him of delicious coffee awaiting him.

77
00:07:23,057 --> 00:07:28,363
His mind and his body are conditioned to wallow in the taste of hot coffee before he settles down to work.

78
00:07:29,826 --> 00:07:31,387
One day, Jim gets to work.

79
00:07:32,108 --> 00:07:33,009
No coffee!

80
00:07:33,192 --> 00:07:34,072
He's so angry.

81
00:07:35,134 --> 00:07:36,536
Whose turn was it to buy the coffee?

82
00:07:37,257 --> 00:07:41,442
He's so embarrassed about his anger when other staff tell him it was his turn.

83
00:07:42,764 --> 00:07:45,708
Now where does this desire, anger and embarrassment come from?

84
00:07:46,629 --> 00:07:51,214
The desire, virtually obsession, has been cultivated by Jim in himself over the years.

85
00:07:52,076 --> 00:07:55,982
Every time he gets to work, he's satisfied his desire, his wish for coffee.

86
00:07:56,541 --> 00:07:57,944
The coffee didn't make Jim do it.

87
00:07:58,704 --> 00:08:00,987
The coffee was not created his obsession.

88
00:08:01,475 --> 00:08:04,980
He could have decided to have coffee only if he felt tired to pep him up.

89
00:08:05,641 --> 00:08:06,982
The coffee is a passive object.

90
00:08:07,944 --> 00:08:13,130
Jim's used it as he's wanted to, and it is Jim himself who is totally responsible for his obsession.

91
00:08:14,793 --> 00:08:16,235
Did the coffee cause Jim's anger?

92
00:08:16,795 --> 00:08:18,718
Did the lack of coffee cause Jim's anger?

93
00:08:18,959 --> 00:08:19,519
Of course not.

94
00:08:20,259 --> 00:08:24,545
Anger was Jim's internal learnt response when he doesn't get what he wants.

95
00:08:25,132 --> 00:08:29,137
When Jim has to suffer the pain of not satisfying a craving, he gets angry.

96
00:08:29,497 --> 00:08:32,900
Worse, the angry mind looks for a scapegoat.

97
00:08:32,921 --> 00:08:34,482
Jim wants to blame someone.

98
00:08:36,504 --> 00:08:38,047
As it turned out, it was his own fault.

99
00:08:38,988 --> 00:08:41,730
And he feels embarrassed about his display of anger and petulance.

100
00:08:42,451 --> 00:08:44,573
Did his colleagues make Jim embarrassed?

101
00:08:44,953 --> 00:08:45,475
Or the coffee?

102
00:08:45,674 --> 00:08:46,515
Or the lack of coffee?

103
00:08:46,775 --> 00:08:47,317
Of course not.

104
00:08:47,636 --> 00:08:52,322
Embarrassment is what Jim feels what he's taught himself to feel when he makes a fool of himself.

105
00:08:54,648 --> 00:08:57,572
It is the mind which suffers from its own internal conditioning.

106
00:08:59,235 --> 00:09:03,159
Next day, Jim reads in the papers an article about the harmfulness of caffeine.

107
00:09:03,640 --> 00:09:05,302
He decides he won't have any more coffee.

108
00:09:05,923 --> 00:09:07,726
But the smell of coffee keeps distracting him.

109
00:09:08,086 --> 00:09:09,328
He feels angry, depressed.

110
00:09:09,629 --> 00:09:12,052
His body, for lack of coffee, feels uncomfortable.

111
00:09:12,332 --> 00:09:13,174
But Jim holds out.

112
00:09:13,495 --> 00:09:15,738
Within a week or two, he's dropped the habit.

113
00:09:16,038 --> 00:09:16,740
He's off the drug.

114
00:09:18,142 --> 00:09:21,886
Reading the article influenced his opinion, his understanding of coffee.

115
00:09:22,423 --> 00:09:25,389
He ponders, he decides, it's better not to drink it.

116
00:09:26,490 --> 00:09:28,974
This decision leads to action, to avoiding coffee.

117
00:09:29,735 --> 00:09:36,164
Although Jim has to suffer the consequences of past conditioning, his past obsession with coffee, he reconditions himself.

118
00:09:36,745 --> 00:09:38,970
Jim purifies his mind of that obsession.

119
00:09:39,650 --> 00:09:40,711
In the end, he's lost it.

120
00:09:41,433 --> 00:09:43,155
He doesn't care whether he has coffee or not.

121
00:09:43,756 --> 00:09:46,861
Jim has reached a state of perfect equanimity about it.

122
00:09:48,225 --> 00:10:03,466
The importance here is to realize that he's conditioned himself, that he's responsible for his own mind, and that he can no longer blame his parents, colleagues, friends, politicians, the system, or whatever, for his state of mind.

123
00:10:03,846 --> 00:10:12,557
In other words, Jane can blame bad management for the collapse of the firm and her eventual redundancy, but not the ensuing depression and so on.

124
00:10:13,057 --> 00:10:16,883
The mental reaction is her own self-imposed conditioning.

125
00:10:19,057 --> 00:10:21,740
This is extremely hard for most people to understand and accept.

126
00:10:22,241 --> 00:10:27,269
Our whole vocabulary and use of language is based on the understanding that others make us angry or happy.

127
00:10:28,070 --> 00:10:30,333
Others make the anger in me, not me.

128
00:10:31,576 --> 00:10:38,125
One of the insights of meditation is to see that states of mind from the darkest to the lightest are our own personal conditioning.

129
00:10:39,366 --> 00:10:42,292
That's why what angers one person may bring joy to another.

130
00:10:42,852 --> 00:10:45,216
One person's delight is another person's poison.

131
00:10:47,052 --> 00:10:53,041
In the Buddha's teaching, this understanding is crucial if we are to cleanse the mind of all its negativity, to purify it.

132
00:10:53,981 --> 00:10:59,269
If Jim thinks his wife Jane is the cause of his depression, he'll have to change her or leave her.

133
00:11:00,412 --> 00:11:05,759
If Jane says John is always making her angry, she'll have to change him before she gets any relief.

134
00:11:07,061 --> 00:11:15,573
This point of view, which presumes that somehow I will be perfectly happy and life perfectly wonderful for me if only the world, especially the people in it, would change.

135
00:11:16,465 --> 00:11:19,229
is one of the causes of our great unhappiness and frustration.

136
00:11:21,032 --> 00:11:27,620
When we realize we are the makers of our own mental states, suddenly we have real power, real opportunity to change.

137
00:11:28,682 --> 00:11:34,331
If I make me angry and depressed, I can make me unangry and undepressed.

138
00:11:36,794 --> 00:11:40,780
When we accept this, we can now look for the kernel agent that produces this conditioning.

139
00:11:41,841 --> 00:11:43,705
The Buddha isolated that agent.

140
00:11:45,000 --> 00:11:48,684
Volition, O disciples, is what I call karma.

141
00:11:48,705 --> 00:11:54,551
It is through will that a person does something in the form of thought, word or action.

142
00:11:56,712 --> 00:11:58,254
So, an idea comes to mind.

143
00:11:58,634 --> 00:12:01,738
At that point, I decide to stop it or develop it.

144
00:12:02,278 --> 00:12:07,945
If I decide to develop it, I will produce a train of thoughts which may translate into words and actions.

145
00:12:09,066 --> 00:12:11,008
From a mental development point of view...

146
00:12:11,342 --> 00:12:16,888
It is so necessary to decide whether the initial thought or idea is good in terms of being right.

147
00:12:17,889 --> 00:12:23,614
However I react, whatever I do will reinforce the conditioning in my mind or undermine it.

148
00:12:25,956 --> 00:12:29,220
This leads us to the next law of karma, that of reciprocity.

149
00:12:29,679 --> 00:12:31,041
Like produces like.

150
00:12:32,241 --> 00:12:38,227
The Buddha taught very clearly that wholesomeness produces wholesomeness and unwholesomeness produces unwholesomeness.

151
00:12:39,220 --> 00:12:49,892
I use wholesomeness, another possible word is skillful, rather than good and bad, to get away from any idea of supernatural forces of good and evil or a rewarding and punishing deity.

152
00:12:50,793 --> 00:12:55,938
The Buddha taught that everything that happens to us is the product of past and present conditions.

153
00:12:57,000 --> 00:12:59,562
There is no concept of punishment in Buddhism.

154
00:13:00,124 --> 00:13:02,746
Everything that happens to us are consequences.

155
00:13:03,335 --> 00:13:07,360
Punishment, as such, is something human beings have produced for themselves.

156
00:13:07,861 --> 00:13:13,089
It's something human beings do to each other out of revenge or a sense of so-called righteousness.

157
00:13:13,870 --> 00:13:17,975
Yet another result, another consequence of unwholesome conditioning in the mind.

158
00:13:20,600 --> 00:13:22,101
An objection is usually raised here.

159
00:13:23,183 --> 00:13:25,407
How is it people get away with murder, literally?

160
00:13:26,107 --> 00:13:28,530
How is it that people who are good end up suffering?

161
00:13:29,472 --> 00:13:32,397
The point is that a person's action has a two-fold effect.

162
00:13:33,187 --> 00:13:36,890
When a person does something two stones drop into two pools.

163
00:13:37,630 --> 00:13:42,996
The first pool is the outside world setting up a chain of reactions that affects the me in the world.

164
00:13:44,238 --> 00:13:48,501
Since I am in relationship with the world as soon as I do something it affects it.

165
00:13:50,144 --> 00:13:53,807
These effects go on and on until they come back to the original doer.

166
00:13:54,307 --> 00:13:57,150
In other words the initial action changes the world.

167
00:13:57,692 --> 00:14:00,914
As the world changes so it affects the doer of that action.

168
00:14:02,092 --> 00:14:05,937
When Jim got angry about his coffee, others formed new opinions of him.

169
00:14:06,597 --> 00:14:10,643
These opinions of theirs now affect his relationship with them.

170
00:14:10,663 --> 00:14:13,846
If his boss was involved, they may even affect his career prospects.

171
00:14:16,408 --> 00:14:22,855
The second stone drops inward into the pool of the mind, setting up a chain reaction which affects the me in myself.

172
00:14:24,357 --> 00:14:28,842
Jim's anger over the coffee goes to reinforce this disposition of anger.

173
00:14:29,431 --> 00:14:41,403
When he goes home and finds there's no coffee there too, his angry response, now just that little more developed, makes for a great explosion and Jim finds himself flinging the empty coffee jar out of the window.

174
00:14:43,004 --> 00:14:53,395
In other words, the unskilful person and the skillful person are simply developing different minds within themselves and they are also developing different worlds around themselves.

175
00:14:54,596 --> 00:14:59,201
At some point, the consequences of their actions will be experienced.

176
00:14:59,941 --> 00:15:03,547
Even if a murderer gets away with it in the world, his mind won't.

177
00:15:05,590 --> 00:15:09,876
The Buddha said, According to the seed, so the fruit is reaped.

178
00:15:11,700 --> 00:15:14,264
There is no escaping these karmic results in Buddhism.

179
00:15:14,725 --> 00:15:19,591
Penance, prayer, offerings to a god of karma won't help in the least.

180
00:15:19,611 --> 00:15:24,480
However, there are ways to assuage, to soften the effects of unwholesome results, the viparka.

181
00:15:25,708 --> 00:15:28,331
Jim's display of petulant anger upset his colleagues.

182
00:15:28,732 --> 00:15:30,134
They were surprised and disappointed.

183
00:15:30,855 --> 00:15:34,919
The next morning, Jim brings two jars of coffee and leaves a note of apology.

184
00:15:35,880 --> 00:15:43,149
Old relationships are re-established, but of course, it will take greater proof to convince them that Jim is not the angry type.

185
00:15:45,532 --> 00:15:53,741
The next question normally asked is, how does Buddhism account for mass suffering, especially seemingly innocent suffering in earthquakes or civilian war casualties?

186
00:15:55,493 --> 00:15:59,658
The first point is that the law of karma is only one of the laws that govern the universe.

187
00:16:00,418 --> 00:16:02,721
When we are born, we have to accept the whole package.

188
00:16:03,582 --> 00:16:08,269
Not everything that happens to us is the result of our personal past or present actions.

189
00:16:09,610 --> 00:16:13,634
When Jim threw that jar out of the window, it landed on the head of a poor old man.

190
00:16:14,355 --> 00:16:15,557
He died there and then.

191
00:16:16,678 --> 00:16:18,321
And Jim went to jail for manslaughter.

192
00:16:19,923 --> 00:16:24,589
Now, he didn't make the man walk under the window just as the jar came down.

193
00:16:25,159 --> 00:16:28,284
So you see, we have to be careful with what we do or say.

194
00:16:28,826 --> 00:16:33,932
There are other factors abroad that can maximize or minimize the effects of what we do.

195
00:16:34,914 --> 00:16:40,082
Wholesome actions, for instance, may not mature since the conditions are not there to support.

196
00:16:42,405 --> 00:16:44,970
The second point is that suffering is a state of mind.

197
00:16:45,991 --> 00:16:52,280
In meditation, when pains come from the sitting posture, we try to see these so-called pains for what they really are.

198
00:16:53,154 --> 00:16:55,857
Calling them pains puts a value judgment on them.

199
00:16:56,057 --> 00:16:57,259
They are bad, terrible.

200
00:16:57,899 --> 00:16:59,761
We react with fear and aversion.

201
00:17:00,442 --> 00:17:14,576
But in meditation, if we concentrate just on the sensations, the pains as sensations, the mind will empty of its normal reaction and we will suddenly experience what we thought of as pain as just sensation.

202
00:17:15,738 --> 00:17:18,980
When we experience just sensations, what is the state of mind?

203
00:17:19,701 --> 00:17:20,522
Peaceful and calm.

204
00:17:21,262 --> 00:17:21,963
Not suffering.

205
00:17:24,121 --> 00:17:29,246
So in a disaster such as the Mexico earthquake of 87, thousands of people suffered pain.

206
00:17:29,945 --> 00:17:32,929
Some died instantly, with very little pain indeed.

207
00:17:33,569 --> 00:17:36,432
Others died slowly in great pain and in great anguish.

208
00:17:37,373 --> 00:17:40,076
Others died in great pain, but equanimously.

209
00:17:41,056 --> 00:17:47,221
How each individual reacted to their tragedy was determined to a large extent by their conditioned state of mind.

210
00:17:48,222 --> 00:17:52,727
From the outside, from the TV pictures, we're filled with horror at so much suffering.

211
00:17:52,960 --> 00:17:59,869
From the inside, there are only individuals, each suffering their own lot according to their self-developed conditioning.

212
00:18:00,832 --> 00:18:05,818
That is why some trapped but not physically suffering may have been screaming with fright.

213
00:18:06,740 --> 00:18:11,126
Others, in terrible physical agony, may have been calm and died peacefully.

214
00:18:13,369 --> 00:18:14,090
So, to recap...

215
00:18:14,527 --> 00:18:24,442
Firstly, the law of karma states that everything we suffer or enjoy belongs to the moral sphere which is governed by the law of cause and effect, as is the world of atoms and molecules.

216
00:18:25,864 --> 00:18:42,188
Secondly, that there is a direct reciprocity in that wholesome, skillful thoughts, words and actions produce wholesome, skillful thoughts, words and actions, and that unwholesomeness and unskillfulness produce unwholesome and unskillful results.

217
00:18:43,500 --> 00:18:49,468
Thirdly, that the root cause of karma is to be discovered in our own volition, our wills.

218
00:18:50,288 --> 00:18:59,940
This means that through the power of our own decision-making, we can change our personality, the way we are and act, and so we can change the world about us.

219
00:19:01,381 --> 00:19:13,255
Fourthly, that the results of any intentioned thoughts, words and actions are inescapable, but we can affect the outcome of unskillfulness in the present with present skillfulness.

220
00:19:16,423 --> 00:19:20,847
Vipassana insight meditation allows us to see our present conditioning of mind.

221
00:19:21,528 --> 00:19:24,711
In the clearing of awareness, the mind displays itself.

222
00:19:25,573 --> 00:19:32,779
By not joining in, not indulging, not developing, we can allow unwholesome states of mind to burn themselves out.

223
00:19:34,021 --> 00:19:40,528
With the practice of loving kindness, metta meditation, we suggest to ourselves more skillful ways of thinking and behaving.

224
00:19:41,669 --> 00:19:45,553
In our daily life, we constantly try to behave in skillful ways.

225
00:19:46,359 --> 00:19:55,434
In this way, the meditative life changes us, moves us away from unwholesome states of mind towards the wholesome, from darkness to light.

226
00:19:58,159 --> 00:20:01,263
The Dhammapada is often referred to as the Buddhist Bible.

227
00:20:02,144 --> 00:20:05,431
It is a collection of many of the Buddhist sayings under different headings.

228
00:20:06,311 --> 00:20:08,115
Here are three verses on karma.

229
00:20:09,731 --> 00:20:16,459
Even a wrongdoer may still find happiness, so long as his unskillful behavior does not bear fruit.

230
00:20:17,480 --> 00:20:23,106
But when his unskillful behavior does bear fruit, he will meet with their unwholesome consequences.

231
00:20:25,930 --> 00:20:32,457
Even a good person may meet with suffering, so long as his skillful behavior does not bear fruit.

232
00:20:33,357 --> 00:20:39,384
But when that skillful behavior does bear fruit, he will enjoy the benefits of that skillful behavior.

233
00:20:42,097 --> 00:20:46,464
If there is no cut on the hand, a person can handle poison.

234
00:20:47,527 --> 00:20:50,330
The poison won't affect someone who does not have a cut.

235
00:20:51,692 --> 00:20:57,803
There are no unwholesome consequences for one who did not intend to act unskillfully.

236
00:21:00,807 --> 00:21:03,551
Well, I hope you found this talk interesting and helpful.

237
00:21:04,692 --> 00:21:06,576
May all of you be happy and peaceful.

238
00:21:07,277 --> 00:21:10,182
May all of you attain the nirvanic peace within.

